A former House of Representatives Deputy Speaker Lasun Yusuf has declined to make any comment on the just-concluded primary election of the ruling All Progressives Congress (APC) in Osun State. Yusuf came third with a total vote of 460; a former Secretary to the State Government (SSG), Moshood Adeoti, scored 12,921, and Governor Adegboyega Oyetola polled 222,169 votes to become the party’s flag bearer in the July 16 governorship election. Speaking on phone with The Nation, the ex-lawmaker said: “I’ve spoken last year and it will take another six months for me before I talk. Thank you!” Also, in a statement yesterday, the senator representing Osun West, Adelere Oriolowo, called for reconciliation of aggrieved party members.   How Oyetola trounced Aregbesola’s man Adeoti     Zoning: Nnamani, Ekweremadu clash over 2023 Enugu…     Enugu shuts markets, offices as council poll holds Wednesday   He also urged members with complaints to see the reelection of Governor Oyetola as a collective project. - Advertisement - Oriolowo congratulated Oyetola for his victory at the primary poll and admonished him to extend his hand of friendship to aggrieved members. “I enjoin our dear governor to use his position as the Number One Citizen of the state to play his fatherly role by extending an olive branch and a hand of friendship to aggrieved members of our party, realising that intra-party crisis has never helped any party in the past. “I also implore our party members, especially the aggrieved members, to see the reelection of our dear governor as a collective project,” he said. SPONSORED